<TITLE> Flood situation likely to improve in 72 hours: FFWC </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 12 (bdnews24.com)  The late monsoon appears to be on the decline with no rain forecast for the next two days, which is expected to improve the flood situation in the next 72 hours, the Flood Forecast and Warning Centre said Wednesday. FFWC assistant engineer Md Arifur Rahman told bdnews24.com: "River waters throughout the country swelled at 34 points, receded at 24, remained unchanged at two and are above danger levels at 23 points." The FFWC said river waters swelled at all points in the Brahmaputra and Ganges basins. In the Meghna basin, the waters increased at some points and receded in other areas. Waters also receded in the southeast hill basins. After an initial increase, water in the Ganges and Brahmaputra rivers will start to recede in the next 72 hours. Water levels remained unchanged at Sylhet point in the Meghna basin. The Meghna river through Sunamganj and Kanaighat receded and remained 3cm above its danger level in Bhairabbazar. Waters at Bhairabbazar point will swell in the next three days. Around Dhaka only the Buriganga river receded. The FFWC advised that other rivers in the metropolitan environs would swell, but not cross the danger mark. bdnews24
